[normal]Written evidence submitted by Meet Middle East through Technology[bold]&#xa0;[bold]SECTION 1: Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]SECTION 2: Introduction[bold]1. The Israeli-Pal
[normal]estinian conflict is arguably one of the most complex and contentious international disputes of our time
[normal]. 
[normal]The British Government is committed to bringing about a negotiated two-state solution 
[normal]resulting in a secure and universally recognized Israeli living 
[normal]alongside a sovereign and viable Palestinian state
[normal]. 
[normal]The UK spends approximately 90 million GBP per year in Israel and the OPTs, with the vast majority understandably going to the latter. In addition to promoting economic growth in the Palestinian Territory
[normal], the UK funds several advocacy-based organizations through its Interdepartmental Conflict Pool.  
[normal]2
[normal]. Given the dire needs of Palestinians living in the 
[normal]OPTs
[normal] and the understanding that building-up Palestinian infrastructure and promoting economic growth is the only way to ensure that the future Palestinian state will be an effective partner for peace, MEET does not take issu
[normal]e with the UK’s budget breakdown in 
[normal]which majority of its funds are aimed at development in the OPTs
[normal]. We do, however, support the senior Parliamentary Committee’s inquiry into whether the Conflict Pool is administered effectively; and 
[normal]we agree with the notion that it ought to shift its focus
[normal] from advocacy projects to programs that bring together Israelis and Palestinians
[normal] in meaningful and sustainable ways
[normal].
[normal]3. While advocacy is an important and effective tool in bringing about social change, it ignores the increasing need – and high-impact opp
[normal]ortunity – to build bridges between Israelis and Palestinians. Rather than continuing to pour limited resources into advocacy organizations, it is preferable that the Conflict Pool funds include support for groups that promote sustainable cross-border part
[normal]nerships between Israelis and Palestinians to instigate real impact. On the ground, Israelis and Palestinians have little to no contact with one another, and their perceptions are primarily fueled by horrific events of the past and the media’s harsh polari
[normal]zation. The current isolation and dehumanization has caused both sides to become apathetic to the other’s needs and fears. With growing disillusionment on both sides, specifically amongst youth, cultivating cross-border relationships is now harder and more
[normal] pressing than ever. A peaceful and economically successful future for Palestinians and Israelis will depend on our ability to generate a motivated cadre of leaders prepared, committed and able to work collectively to address the complex issues of their in
[normal]dividual and collective societies.
[normal]4. The lack of bi-national networks of Palestinians and Israelis who share the motivation and capacity to work together towards solving mutual problems is a major challenge on the way to achieving a nonviolent resolution 
[normal]of the conflict. 
[normal]In the current reality, the absence of shared networks and sustained opportunities to interact severely limits the abilities of 
[normal]these 
[normal]Palestinian and Israeli youth (the future leaders of our region) to build the trust and cultivate the rel
[normal]ationships needed to work effectively on joint goals and to solve common challenges. 
[normal]A 
[normal]peaceful resolution of the conflict will rely on our ability to build lasting bridges between young Palestinians and Israelis, utilizing our common resources to create p
[normal]artnerships built on positive, pragmatic change in the region.
[normal]5. At MEET, we believe that the main way to strengthen isolated Israeli and Palestinian communities is to work together on shared interests by securing high-skilled, academic, employment and en
[normal]trepreneurship opportunities for Israeli and Palestinian youth. MEET is an innovative program aimed at educating and empowering tomorrow’s most promising Israeli and Palestinian leaders. Working together with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)
[normal] since 2004, MEET’s goal is to develop an active professional network among
[normal] its excellening
[normal] students, while empowering them to i
[normal]ndividually and collectively 
[normal]create positive economic, political and social change within their communities and, eventually, the
[normal] Middle East. In 2014, over 400 youth will be working together towards this goal
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]S[bold]ECTION[bold] 3: Factual Information[bold]About MEET
[normal]6
[normal]. MEET is a three-year educational program that brings together Israeli and Palestinian young leaders through the common language
[normal]s
[normal] of computer science and entrepreneurship. 
[normal]Referenced by US President Obama as an example of 
[normal]how
[normal] 
[normal]innovation is reshaping the Middle East, MEET
[normal] is managed and run by a devoted professional team – Israeli and Palestinian 
[normal]C
[normal]o-
[normal]CEOs
[normal] 
[normal]and a bi-national staff – as 
[normal]well as a large group of international volunteers from MIT 
[normal](Massachusetts Institute of Technology) 
[normal]and the Middle East
[normal]. O
[normal]versight is provided by an executive board of Palestinians and Israelis. MEET has also established long
[normal]-
[normal]term relationships with key 
[normal]institutional partners, such as MIT, the Hebrew University, HP, Goo
[normal]gle 
[normal]and others.
[normal] In this way, MEET models the 
[normal]cross-border 
[normal]network that we believe is critical to a pathway to peac
[normal]e, and all too rare in the current environment
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We
[normal] employ a “learn-by-doing
[normal]” approach that challenges students to move beyond theory and to engage in hands-on activities. Students are 
[normal]taught
[normal] 
[normal]to think big while working together on real
[normal]-world
[normal] projects with leading companies. The program comprises two stages: 1) the Student Program 
[normal]which runs in parallel to high school over the course of three years; and 2) the Alumni Program, which ensures the achievement of MEET’s long-term mission. The entire program incorporates a values-based ‘Deeper Understanding’ curriculum focused on dialogue
[normal] and conflict resolution.
[normal]Student Recruitment
[normal]7
[normal]. The selection of participants is comprised of a 
[normal]six
[normal]-month recruitment process that engages 
[normal]Palestinian and Israeli
[normal] 
[normal]high school
[normal] students 
[normal]and identifies the top candidates to participate in the three-year prog
[normal]ram, ensuring equal representation of Israelis and Palestinians; males and females. Students are recruited from over 40 high schools from East and West Jerusalem, Ramallah, Bethlehem, Mevesseret, Beit Shemesh, Nazareth and more
[normal], engaging the OPT population
[normal]s central to the Conflict Pool
[normal]. Applicants undergo a rigorous selection process, including a written exam, a group dynamics session and a personal interview. As an excellence 
[normal]model, admittance is highly competitive (in 2013, 999 students applied while MEET
[normal] only accepted 70 participants). All students receive a full scholarship, regardless of 
[normal]socio-economic background
[normal].
[normal] This means youth populations who would otherwise never meet, let alone collaborate, have 
[normal]equal access to world-class education and empowermen
[normal]t towards a common goal of
[normal] a
[normal] peace
[normal]ful future based on positive economic, political and social change
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Student Program
[normal]8
[normal]. 
[normal]The three-year 
[normal]Student P
[normal]rogram begins with an intensive summer course taught by volunteer instructors from MIT at the Hebrew Universit
[normal]y of Jerusalem
[normal]. Participants learn the
[normal] basics of teamwork, business, technology and leadership. 
[normal]S
[normal]tudents meet during 
[normal]the school year, after school 
[normal]for 3.5 hours each week 
[normal]at our tech hubs in Jerusalem and Nazareth to learn advanced technology skills and work on joint projects. Based on methodical research and practical evidence, as well as 
[normal]10
[normal] 
[normal]years of experience in the field, 
[normal]MEET employs a strength-based conception of yout
[normal]h development, recognizing their potential to impact society and alter social frameworks.
[normal] Our academic model was designed by experts in the fields of education, business, technology, entrepreneurship, conflict resolution and dialogue.
[normal]9
[normal]. The academic level
[normal] at ME
[normal]E
[normal]T is highly challenging. 
[normal]Students engage in over 800 
[normal]academic 
[normal]hours, 
[normal]providing them with high-level computer science, entrepreneurship and leadership skills. 
[normal]Dealing with high standards and demand
[normal]s
[normal] helps students to develop 
[normal]critical thinking, 
[normal]proble
[normal]m solving
[normal] and work ethic
[normal], which translate into thinking creatively 
[normal]about changing the Palestinian-Israeli status quo
[normal]. Exposure to the 
[normal]computer 
[normal]programming work has encouraged students to enroll in computer studies in school, affording them increased opport
[normal]unities for personal academic enrichment and professional advancement
[normal] – of particular benefit to students in the OPTs who often do not have access to this quality of computer science
[normal]. Students have remarked that the program made them ‘learn how to learn’, 
[normal]both individually and by seeking the assistance of others.
[normal]10
[normal]. Teamwork is one of the primary tools in the program’s work model and its main objective is to encourage 
[normal]collaboration
[normal] between students from different groups. The integration between Israelis an
[normal]d Palestinians poses a chall
[normal]enge for most students
[normal], as it requires them to contend with contradicting opinions and even carry out decisions taken by the group that run contrary to their own preferences. The most successful teams are usually those that have
[normal] talked through the difficulties and have undergone a mutual process from beginning to end. Evaluations demonstrate that the degree of cooperation substantially increases with familiarity and experience. Dealing with these challenges is a significant educa
[normal]tional and personal process for students. Throughout the course, 
[normal]participants learn how to contend with opinions and positions that are different, at times even contradictory, to their own, to conduct themselves as a group that affords equal importance to 
[normal]a variety of opinions, and to move forward by 
[normal]persuading 
[normal]others
[normal] to adopt a fresh viewpoint
[normal]. Evaluations demonstrate that the longer students have been participating in the program, the more at ease they are working with members of other teams.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Deeper Und
[normal]erstanding
[normal] Curriculum
[normal]11
[normal]. In addition to the academic and professional components of the program, MEET has developed a ‘Deeper Understanding’ (DU) curriculum that focuses on promoting dialogue and conflict resolution. It is a 
[normal]values-based education that teaches youth how to communicate and deal with different subjects, such as respect, 
[normal]identity 
[normal]and “the other.”
[normal] The main purpose of these sessions is to provide students with a framework where the
[normal]y can express themselves openly
[normal], a
[normal]nd to discuss the difficulties Israelis and Palestinians
[normal] experience
[normal] as a means of learning and attaining tools to deal with conflict situations in real life. It allows subjects and stress points that are naturally kept under the surface to become exposed i
[normal]n order to equip the youth with tools to express themselves in relation to a complex situation
[normal], and 
[normal]expand their critical thinking abilities as a result of 
[normal]encountering new
[normal] 
[normal]perspectives
[normal]. The direct effect of the DU sessions is that they strengthen social c
[normal]onnections between students, which allows them to expand the range of topics they are able to discuss to include deeper and more sensitive subjects of a social and political nature. DU encourages students to behave in a responsible and mature manner, decre
[normal]ases disciplinary issues, and fosters a more productive environment. 
[normal]12
[normal]. Evaluations reveal that the DU sessions have a positive influence on the relationship and soci
[normal]al atmosphere within the group. 
[normal]S
[normal]tudents recognize that it is possible to speak, argue a
[normal]nd disagree while still maintaining mutual respect and civilized discourse.
[normal] One of the most important skills acquired through these sessions is the ability to properly convey a message so that it is clear and authentic, 
[normal]and expressed
[normal] in a respectful and no
[normal]n-insulting manner. These skills are designed to help with interpersonal and inter-group conflicts, and to 
[normal]cultivate 
[normal]habits
[normal] that translate into personal and professional 
[normal]norms
[normal] in their MEET teams, 
[normal]alumni ventures, 
[normal]higher education, and eventually positions
[normal] of leadership.
[normal]Alumni Program
[normal]13
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]he Alumni Program is designed to achieve our long-term mission, allowing us to continue impacting our participants 
[normal]throughout their lives and 
[normal]in their academic and professional 
[normal]pursuits
[normal]. We have a gro
[normal]wing network of over
[normal] 200 alumni, 75% of whom are living in the region and actively engaged in various MEET Alumni activities. The program is comprised of three pillars: 
[normal]network building, pro
[normal]fessional development and a bi-n
[normal]ational Venture Lab
[normal]. 
[normal]Network Building
[normal] takes place through quarterly conferences and online platforms; 
[normal]Professional Development
[normal] occurs via monthly workshops, courses and a 
[normal]six
[normal]-month mentorship program; and the 
[normal]Venture Lab
[normal] (launched in partnership with Google), is a space designed to incubate t
[normal]echnology, business and social projects (commissioned and self-initiated) led by the growing number of MEET alumni.
[normal] The Venture Lab is an important 
[normal]endeavor
[normal] that allows us to affect meaningful change in the region.
[normal] MEET alumni have already 
[normal]built six projec
[normal]ts in the Venture L
[normal]ab and are currently developing five projects in bi-national teams.
[normal] 
[normal]In ad
[normal]dition to enrolling in various 
[normal]a
[normal]lumni activities through MEET, we track our alumni as they embark on their individual academic and career paths, an investment we de
[normal]em critical to understanding the long-term effectiveness of MEET’s efforts. 
[normal]Effectiveness of a Long-Term Program
[normal]15
[normal]. 
[normal]M
[normal]eeting over this extended period of time 
[normal](three-year program and ongoing Alumni Program) 
[normal]is extremely significant
[normal] in shaping the minds an
[normal]d attitudes of participants
[normal]. Evaluations clearly demonstrate that the longer the students have been in the program, the more frequent and significant social interactions become. At a certain point in the program, trust is born through mutual familiarity an
[normal]d interaction between the youth, creating a shift in the perceptions and opinions for the other group. Most students arrive at the program never having met someone from the other nationality. Many described their surprise at having discovered the many s
[normal]imi
[normal]larities between themselves.
[normal]16
[normal]. 
[normal]One of the most significant accomplishments of the program is the participants reaching a mutual understanding that they are not essentially different from their counterparts on the other side, and that they have the abilit
[normal]y to communicate with one another and connect on a personal level. MEET succeeds in overcoming the primary obstacle of perceiving others as essentially different from oneself (dehumanizing the other). During the course of the program, youth from both sides
[normal] come to the realization that they deal with similar problems, are troubled by similar issues, and enjoy similar activities. This realization is a significant milestone for a more comprehensive social change. Understanding points of similarity creates fert
[normal]ile ground for the emergence of personal ties and deeper acquaintance.
[normal]17. Both internal and external evaluations of our programs have indicated that MEET causes students to: understand each other’s narratives; care about the future of their respective and
[normal] shared societies; commit to giving back to their communities; believe that joint Israeli and Palestinian efforts will lead to a better and more peaceful region for all; have higher self-esteem and self-confidence; and are driven to become successful in bu
[normal]siness. This coming together of communities is an important step toward building a lasting peace in the region. 
[normal]Budget
[normal]The following budget calculations are based on MEET’s 2014 proposed budget, and exchange rate of 1 USD = 0.61 GBP. MEET’s proposed 2014 
[normal]annual budget is $1,613,664 (£979,581); Summer Program is $597,601 (£362,776); Yearlong Program is $359,287 (£218,106); Alumni Program is $143,666 (£87,213).
