[normal]SECTION 4: Recommendations[bold]18
[normal]. Historic changes are sweeping the Middle East, 
[normal]while
[normal] the region’s youth are learning to harness the power of technology as a tool to mobilize positive social and economic change. MEET’s goal is to empower young Palestinian and Israeli leaders to leverage their bi-national and global networks, and to use edu
[normal]cation as a means of promoting positive change in local Palestinian and Israeli 
[normal]communities. We are strategically and effectively building a generation of future Israeli and Palestinian leaders who are empowered, equipped and positioned to work together on
[normal] joint regional challenges with a clear desire to promote peaceful and positive change. Advocacy, although important in persuading governments to adopt more human policies, is not enough to ensure lasting peace in the region. The lives of Israelis and Pale
[normal]stinians are inherently intertwined. We believe that youth on both sides must become professionally and personally connected through working on joint projects and acquiring a mutual set of skills and values.
[normal]19
[normal]. 
[normal]The MEET model has proven its strength and r
[normal]esilience in the face of some of the most challenging political and economic times
[normal]. Having invested strongly in relationship-building with students, parents, schools, and multi-national corporations, MEET has developed a strong branch name associated with 
[normal]integrity, clarity of mission, and excellence in delivering a 
[normal]high-quality educational 
[normal]program. Currently, we are the only long-term, local
[normal],
[normal] skills-based educational 
[normal]program
[normal] that brings together Israeli and Pale
[normal]stinian youth for the explicit
[normal] purpose of jointly finding transformative solutions to social, economic and political problems facing both sides.
[normal]2
[normal]0
[normal]. 
[normal]We believe that MEET is a strong and viable partner for the British Government in its 
[normal]pursuit of a lasting peace between Israelis and Pal
[normal]estinians
[normal]. We have previously met with representatives of the British Embassy in Tel Aviv and were encouraged to submit a proposal for funding in March 2013. Unfortunately, our request was denied due to the fact that the British Embassy was considering a d
[normal]ifferent approach to working with NGOs in Israel and the OPTs. We hope that, based on evidence such as that provided in this document, the British government will reconsider funding projects such as ours that bring together Israelis and Palestinians to cre
[normal]ate positive change.
